{
  "doc_id": "55803",
  "text": "The findings of our study suggest that patients undergoing outpatient sedation or anesthesia are at very low risk of complications that require unexpected hospital admission or visits to the emergency department when following an established protocol. Previously, patients have been instructed that they should have a responsible person available to escort them from their procedure and be available to help with their care for 24 hours after their procedure. [CITATION_1] With proper preparation, the use of more short-acting anesthetic/sedation medications, and sound clinical judgment, this axiom may no longer be true.",
  "correct_citation": {
